project: H = Hearts, C = Clubs, S = Spades, D = Diamonds

This is the main layout of the game.  There’s a lot going on here, so let’s get cracking.
I highly recommend to read the readme layout first.

The background layer consists out of the green background as well as the white details pane at the right hand side of the screen.  This detail info contains a number of things.  The teams, the dealer, the current trump card, wether players tapped or not, and the last cards that were dealt in the previous turnset.

The trump icon is a sprite with 6 frames.  One for every possible suit,  including “no trump”, and blank for this situations where no trump card should be shown, for example when the round has just started.  The last_card sprites also contain 32 frames.  One for every card in the game, and a blank one for the same purpose.

There are 8 layers for placeholders.  Each layer is used separately for each turnset of a round.  This makes sure that the cards are always neatly stacked together without leaving holes in the series of cards.  

The cards itself are placed in the cards layer.  A card has 2 animation frames.  One for front facing and one for back facing.  Turning a card around virtually is thus just a matter of changing the animation frame.  Cards also hold a contrast effect, which is used to dim the contrast of the card when the card is evaluated as being invalid for the current move.

There are a number ob black blocks all around the table, one for each player.  This is a reference point.  There is a reference point for each player.  this represents the x and y coördinate of the location where the cards have to move to when the turnset is complete.  

The pink block is the dealer starting point from which the cards are dealt, and moved to their respective placeholders.

The background also hold playername labels, that are filled with the aliasses of the correct players when the game starts.  

Next to that, there is also an invisible generic title just above the player name at the bottom.  It is used to display extra information, for example showing the player that is next up to make a move.
